# Edge-Native IoT Framework for Aircraft Engine Remaining Useful Life (RUL) Prediction Using a Hybrid Digital Twin

## Project Overview

This project aims to develop an intelligent predictive maintenance system for aircraft engines using Edge Computing, Industrial IoT (IIoT), Machine Learning, and a Hybrid Digital Twin. The system predicts the Remaining Useful Life (RUL) of an aircraft engine, enabling maintenance before a failure occurs. This approach helps improve engine reliability, reduce maintenance costs, and enhance flight safety.

## Problem Statement

Aircraft engines operate under varying environmental and operational conditions, making it difficult to accurately predict their health. Traditional maintenance methods are often time-based, which can lead to unnecessary maintenance or unexpected engine failures. This project proposes an Edge-Native IoT Framework integrated with a Hybrid Digital Twin to continuously monitor engine data and predict the Remaining Useful Life (RUL) using machine learning.

## Objectives

* Collect and process aircraft engine sensor data.
* Monitor engine health in real time.
* Predict the Remaining Useful Life (RUL) of aircraft engines.
* Reduce unexpected engine failures.
* Support predictive maintenance using AI and Digital Twin technology.

## Technologies Used

* Python
* Machine Learning
* Edge Computing
* Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT)
* Hybrid Digital Twin
* XGBoost / Random Forest
* NASA C-MAPSS Dataset
* Git & GitHub

## Dataset

This project uses the NASA C-MAPSS (Commercial Modular Aero-Propulsion System Simulation) dataset for training and evaluating the machine learning models.

## Project Structure

* `dataset/` - NASA C-MAPSS dataset
* `src/` - Source code
* `models/` - Trained machine learning models
* `docs/` - Project documentation
* `notebooks/` - Jupyter notebooks
* `README.md` - Project documentation

